So a quick thought on this. We want tests to only test a single "unit" of work. So, for example, the code here is basically identical to the code to test saveAlert() which tells me that something has gone wrong. I would model these tests on the tests that we have for HibernateConceptDAOTest.
In particular, this uses DBUnit to put the database in a known state and adds the @Autowired annotation to the dao being tested.
Then, the test for the various get methods becomes just a matter of getting known values from the database (because they are configured using a DBUnit XML document) and so if we break the save functionality, it doesn't also break this test.
Also on naming conventions, the key part about the getAlert() method is that it gets the alert by the id field so I would name this something like:
public void getAlert_shouldGetAlertById()
Similarly, saveAlert() probably needs at least two tests:
public void saveAlert_shouldSaveAlertToDb()

public void saveAlert_shouldRaiseExceptionWhenAlertInvalid()

